[V] — a vector #mutable #type:list
[M] — a matrix
[R] — accumulated results

[*] This is a comprehensive example
demonstrating all JAW constructs
in a single file

/process #pure
[V]: a list, [M]: a matrix
	[1] — [L]: length of [V]
	[^] upper bound for iteration
	[2] — [P]: tracking position = 0

	[~] — [P] < [L]
		[1] — [V]@[P] > 0 ? /HandlePositive | /HandleNegative
		[^] branch on sign
		[2] — [P] += 1

	[&]
		[1] — Fetch data from API
		[2] — Load cache from disk
	[3] — Process results
	[^] step 3 waits for parallel block

	[>] [R] #validated

/HandlePositive
	[!] —
		processing positive value
		[V]@[P] added to [R]
	[1] — [R] << [V]@[P]

/HandleNegative
	[!] — #warn skipping negative value at [P]
	[1] — pass

[*] The /process function calls /HandlePositive and /HandleNegative
internally, branching on whether [V]@[P] is positive or negative.
[R] accumulates results across iterations.

/main
[V]: a list, [M]: a matrix
	[1] — /process[ [V], [M] ]
	[^] call /process with [V] and [M]
	[!] — result: [R]
	[^] log the value of [R]
	[2] — validate[ [R] ]
	[^] [R] is passed to another function for validation
	[>] [2]
